newsitem.title: AUSTRIA: Austrian bonds end higher, seen upbeat.
newsitem.headline: Austrian bonds end higher, seen upbeat.

text.p: VIENNA, July 30 (Reuter) Austrian bonds ended firmer on Wednesday but off the day's highs after the market came under pressure from profit taking.
U.S. inflation data gave the market a boost, traders said, noting interest concentrated on the long end.
"The figures were expected. There was nothing much else driving the market today," said one trader.
Dealers said a rumour that Austria might issue a Eurobond worth $500 million was causing short-term jitters. The Federal Financing Agency has denied the rumour.
Traders predicted the mood would be positive if slightly restrained ahead of a rash of U.S. data due to be released in the next few days.
* 10-year benchmark 5.625 pct bond maturing July 2007 up 25 bps at 100.40 to yield 5.57 (5.60) pct in bourse trade, quoted post-market at 100.59/69 to yield 5.55/53 pct.
* Five-year 4.625 bond maturing May 2002 up 15 bps at 99.75 to yield 4.68 (4.72) pct in bourse trade, quoted post-market at 99.74/82 to yield 4.68/66 percent.
* Austrian bond future up 31 bps at 110.40.
* 10-year spread over Germany steady at six bps, five-year spread down one at 20 bps.
* Money market rates mixed with three-month VIBOR steady at 3.400 and overnight money sightly firmer at 3.13/3.38. -- Vienna newsroom, +431 53112 257
